revision.text:
The '''Animal Crush Video Prohibition Act of 2010''', {{USStatute|111|294|124|3177|2010|12|09}}, was a United States law that addressed the banning of depictions of [[cruelty to animals]] to satisfy a [[crush fetish]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama signs law banning 'crush videos' depicting animal cruelty|first=Bill|last=Mears|date=December 10, 2010|work=[[CNN News]]|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2010-12-10/politics/animal.cruelty_1_dog-fighting-videos-crush-videos-animal-cruelty}}</ref> The [[Bill (law)|bill]], {{USBill|111|hr|5566}}, was introduced by Rep. [[Elton Gallegly]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[California|CA]]),<ref>{{cite news|title=Local congressman introduces new bill to stop the sale of animal cruelty videos|first=Richard|last=Simon|date=April 21, 2010|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/unleashed/2010/04/animal-cruelty-videos-law-supreme.html}}</ref> and primarily modifies {{usc|18|48}}.
==Background== {{main|United States v. Stevens}}
The act revised the version of 18 U.S.C. § 48 which had entered into effect on December 9, 1999 was an [[unconstitutional]] abridgment of the [[First Amendment of the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] right to freedom of speech by the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]]. The previous law, placed into effect by {{USPL|106|152}} enacted on December 9, 1999, aimed at banning the [[publication]], sale, and ownership of so-called "[[crush videos]]", which are films that feature a person or another animal crushing or trampling another smaller animal to [[death]].<ref>[http://www.stopcrush.org/?page_id=2 About Crush « STOPCRUSH.ORG<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.pet-abuse.com/pages/animal_cruelty/crush_videos.php Stopping Crush Videos], [http://www.pet-abuse.com Pet-Abuse.Com].</ref> In 2010, the Supreme Court ruled that the law was too vague and broad in ''[[United States v. Stevens]]'', and, in an 8–1 decision, it nullified the 1999 law.<ref>Adam Liptak, [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/21/us/21scotus.html Justices Reject Ban on Videos of Animal Cruelty], April 20, 2010 The New York Times.</ref>
